### What happened?

When the `DRANodeAllocatableResources` feature is enabled, the scheduler computes a pod's node-allocatable footprint from `resourceClaim.Status.Allocation.Devices.Results[i].ConsumedCapacity`, multiplied by `NodeAllocatableResourceMappings[...].AllocationMultiplier`. `ConsumedCapacity` is not validated at the API server, so a negative value flows into that computation and produces a negative footprint.

The API validation gap is at `pkg/apis/resource/validation/validation.go:518` (`validateDeviceRequestAllocationResult`), which does not look at `ConsumedCapacity` at all. There are zero references to `ConsumedCapacity` in the validation package.

The footprint is computed at `pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/dynamicresources/nodeallocatabledynamicresources.go:158-171`: `quantity = consumed.DeepCopy()` then optionally multiplied by `AllocationMultiplier`, and added into the claim status resources at line 178.

The fit check that consumes the footprint only runs when the demand is positive. `nodeFitsResources` guards each resource with `podRequest.MilliCPU > 0` (line 340) and `podRequest.Memory > 0` (line 350). A negative footprint makes those guards false, so the fit check for that resource is skipped. A malformed or corrupt AllocationResult can therefore produce a negative node-allocatable footprint whose fit check is silently not performed.

### What did you expect to happen?

Two layers. At the API server, `ConsumedCapacity` (and the related `CapacityRequirements.Requests` and `AllocationMultiplier`) should be validated as non-negative. In the scheduler as defense in depth, `buildNodeAllocatableDRAInfo` should return an error on a negative consumed capacity, re-check the sign after applying the multiplier, and never hand a negative aggregate to `nodeFitsResources`.

### How can we reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)?

This test goes through the real `buildNodeAllocatableDRAInfo` with a device that maps CPU to a capacity key, and a claim allocated to it with `ConsumedCapacity["cores"] = -8`. The computed CPU footprint is `-8`.

<details>
<summary>Repro test (package dynamicresources)</summary>

```go
func TestNegativeConsumedCapacityFootprint(t *testing.T) {
	slice := &resourceapi.ResourceSlice{
		ObjectMeta: metav1.ObjectMeta{Name: "slice-a", Namespace: "test-ns"},
		Spec: resourceapi.ResourceSliceSpec{
			Pool: resourceapi.ResourcePool{Name: "pool1"}, NodeName: ptr.To("test-node"), Driver: "driver.example.com",
			Devices: []resourceapi.Device{{Name: "dev0",
				NodeAllocatableResourceMappings: map[v1.ResourceName]resourceapi.NodeAllocatableResourceMapping{
					v1.ResourceCPU: {CapacityKey: ptr.To(resourceapi.QualifiedName("cores"))},
				}}},
		}}
	alloc := &resourceapi.AllocationResult{Devices: resourceapi.DeviceAllocationResult{
		Results: []resourceapi.DeviceRequestAllocationResult{{
			Driver: "driver.example.com", Pool: "pool1", Device: "dev0",
			ConsumedCapacity: map[resourceapi.QualifiedName]resource.Quantity{"cores": resource.MustParse("-8")},
		}}}}
	claim := &resourceapi.ResourceClaim{ObjectMeta: metav1.ObjectMeta{Name: "claim1", Namespace: "test-ns", UID: "claim1-uid"}}
	pod := st.MakePod().Name("test-pod").Namespace("test-ns").UID("test-uid").
		Containers([]v1.Container{{Name: "c1", Resources: v1.ResourceRequirements{Claims: []v1.ResourceClaim{{Name: "claim1"}}}}}).Obj()
	pl := &DynamicResources{draManager: &mockDRAManager{claims: []*resourceapi.ResourceClaim{claim}, resourceSlices: []*resourceapi.ResourceSlice{slice}}}
	got, err := pl.buildNodeAllocatableDRAInfo(pod,
		map[v1.ObjectReference]*resourceapi.AllocationResult{{Name: "claim1", UID: "claim1-uid"}: alloc},
		map[string]types.UID{"claim1": "claim1-uid"})
	if err != nil {
		t.Fatal(err)
	}
	cpu := got[0].Resources[v1.ResourceCPU] // "-8": a negative node-allocatable footprint
	if cpu.Sign() >= 0 {
		t.Errorf("expected a negative footprint, got %s", cpu.String())
	}
}
```

</details>

I also confirmed the API accepts the value: `validateDeviceRequestAllocationResult` has no `ConsumedCapacity` check, so a status update carrying a negative `ConsumedCapacity` is not rejected.

### Anything else we need to know?

The value is not controlled by an ordinary namespace workload author. It lives in the allocation portion of ResourceClaim status, so reaching this code with a negative value requires an actor or component authorized to write that allocation status, or another allocator bug that persists a negative consumed capacity. The feature gate `DRANodeAllocatableResources` is alpha and off by default. This is best read as corrupt or malformed trusted control-plane state being treated as a negative resource credit, not a tenant-facing issue.

The spec-side `ExactDeviceRequest.Capacity` (`CapacityRequirements.Requests`) is also unvalidated at the API server, though the structured allocator now rejects a negative request in `CmpRequestOverCapacity`. The remaining gap for that field is only the missing API bound.

