### What happened?

When computing a pod's node-allocatable footprint from DRA claims, the scheduler looks up the allocated device by pool name and device name only, and does not consider the driver. A DRA device is identified by `(driver, pool, device)`, so two drivers that publish the same pool name and device name on a node collide, and the lookup can return the wrong driver's device.

`getDeviceFromManager` in `pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/dynamicresources/nodeallocatabledynamicresources.go`:

```go
func getDeviceFromManager(draManager fwk.SharedDRAManager, poolName, deviceName string) (*resourceapi.Device, error) {
	slices, err := draManager.ResourceSlices().ListWithDeviceTaintRules()
	...
	for _, slice := range slices {
		if slice.Spec.Pool.Name == poolName {
			for i := range slice.Spec.Devices {
				if slice.Spec.Devices[i].Name == deviceName {
					return &slice.Spec.Devices[i], nil
				}
			}
		}
	}
	...
}
```

It compares `slice.Spec.Pool.Name` and `device.Name`, but never `slice.Spec.Driver`, and returns the first match. Both call sites pass `result.Pool` and `result.Device` but not `result.Driver`, which is available on the allocation result. The returned device carries the wrong `NodeAllocatableResourceMappings`, so the pod's node CPU/memory footprint is computed from the wrong driver's mapping. The result depends on the order of the resource-slice list, so it is non-deterministic.

### What did you expect to happen?

The lookup should match the allocation's driver as well, so `getDeviceFromManager` returns the device from the slice whose `(driver, pool, device)` matches the allocation result.

### How can we reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)?

Add this test to `pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/dynamicresources` (it uses the existing `mockDRAManager`). Two drivers publish the same pool name and device name on the node with different node-allocatable CPU multipliers (1 and 8), and a claim is allocated the driver-b device, so the pod's node-allocatable CPU footprint should be 8:

<details>
<summary>Repro test</summary>

```go
func TestBuildNodeAllocatableDRAInfoDriverCollision(t *testing.T) {
	mkSlice := func(name, driver, mult string) *resourceapi.ResourceSlice {
		return &resourceapi.ResourceSlice{
			ObjectMeta: metav1.ObjectMeta{Name: name, Namespace: "test-ns"},
			Spec: resourceapi.ResourceSliceSpec{
				Pool: resourceapi.ResourcePool{Name: "pool1"}, NodeName: ptr.To("test-node"), Driver: driver,
				Devices: []resourceapi.Device{{Name: "cpu0",
					NodeAllocatableResourceMappings: map[v1.ResourceName]resourceapi.NodeAllocatableResourceMapping{
						v1.ResourceCPU: {AllocationMultiplier: ptr.To(resource.MustParse(mult))},
					}}},
			}}
	}
	// Same pool name and device name, different drivers and multipliers.
	slices := []*resourceapi.ResourceSlice{
		mkSlice("slice-a", "driver-a.example.com", "1"),
		mkSlice("slice-b", "driver-b.example.com", "8"),
	}
	// The claim is allocated the device from driver-b.
	alloc := &resourceapi.AllocationResult{Devices: resourceapi.DeviceAllocationResult{
		Results: []resourceapi.DeviceRequestAllocationResult{{
			Driver: "driver-b.example.com", Pool: "pool1", Device: "cpu0",
		}}}}
	claim := &resourceapi.ResourceClaim{ObjectMeta: metav1.ObjectMeta{Name: "claim1", Namespace: "test-ns", UID: "claim1-uid"}}
	pod := st.MakePod().Name("test-pod").Namespace("test-ns").UID("test-uid").
		Containers([]v1.Container{{Name: "c1", Resources: v1.ResourceRequirements{Claims: []v1.ResourceClaim{{Name: "claim1"}}}}}).Obj()

	pl := &DynamicResources{draManager: &mockDRAManager{claims: []*resourceapi.ResourceClaim{claim}, resourceSlices: slices}}
	got, err := pl.buildNodeAllocatableDRAInfo(pod,
		map[v1.ObjectReference]*resourceapi.AllocationResult{{Name: "claim1", UID: "claim1-uid"}: alloc},
		map[string]types.UID{"claim1": "claim1-uid"})
	if err != nil {
		t.Fatal(err)
	}
	want := []v1.NodeAllocatableResourceClaimStatus{{
		ResourceClaimName: "claim1",
		Containers:        []string{"c1"},
		Resources:         map[v1.ResourceName]resource.Quantity{v1.ResourceCPU: resource.MustParse("8")},
	}}
	if diff := cmp.Diff(want, got); diff != "" {
		t.Errorf("node-allocatable footprint used the wrong driver's mapping (-want +got):\n%s", diff)
	}
}
```

</details>

On the current code the computed CPU footprint is `1` instead of `8`: the allocation is for driver-b (multiplier 8), but `getDeviceFromManager` returns driver-a's device (the first slice with the same pool and device name), so the pod's node-allocatable footprint is taken from the wrong driver's mapping.

### Anything else we need to know?

`getDeviceFromManager` and its two call sites already have the driver available on the allocation result. Passing the driver through and adding `slice.Spec.Driver == driverName` to the match resolves it.

This is a scheduler-plugin issue reproduced with a unit test; it does not require a running cluster, DRA driver, container runtime, or cloud provider.

Feature gate:

```text
DRANodeAllocatableResources=true
```

`DRANodeAllocatableResources` is alpha and disabled by default in Kubernetes 1.36, so the affected path is opt-in.

